
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Toward a Model of Business Unit Performance: An Integrative Approach
AU  - White, Roderick E.
AU  - Hamermesh, Richard C.
Y1  - 1981/04/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1981.4287787
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1981.4287787
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 213
EP  - 223
VL  - 6
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A number of largely independent areas of research have attempted to ex-plain business performance, usually emphasizing different factors, using different conceptual schemes and language, and examining different organizational units. Our model of performance integrates overlapping and common explanatory variables from industrial organization economics, organization theory, and business policy: business position, industry environment, strategy, and structure. The business unit of multibusiness firms is our unit of analysis.
AB  - A number of largely independent areas of research have attempted to ex-plain business performance, usually emphasizing different factors, using different conceptual schemes and language, and examining different organizational units. Our model of performance integrates overlapping and common explanatory variables from industrial organization economics, organization theory, and business policy: business position, industry environment, strategy, and structure. The business unit of multibusiness firms is our unit of analysis.
