T1  - Task Environments and Budgetary Decision Making,
AU  - Bromiley, Philip
Y1  - 1981/04/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1981.4287836
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1981.4287836
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 277
EP  - 288
VL  - 6
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Often research using budgetary process models either assumes that the models reflect the actual decision processes of budgeters or is vague about exactly what is being modelled. I argue that budgetary models model the task environment of budgeters ? the problems they face rather than their decision processes, and I examine the implications of this proposition for budgetary research and practical uses of budgetary models.
AB  - Often research using budgetary process models either assumes that the models reflect the actual decision processes of budgeters or is vague about exactly what is being modelled. I argue that budgetary models model the task environment of budgeters ? the problems they face rather than their decision processes, and I examine the implications of this proposition for budgetary research and practical uses of budgetary models.
