T1  - The Use of Impact and Self-Impact Correlations In Causal Analysis
AU  - Ito, Jack K.
AU  - Srinivas, Kalburgi M.
Y1  - 1981/04/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1981.4287855
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1981.4287855
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 301
EP  - 308
VL  - 6
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - It has recently been suggested that impact and self-impact correlations be extended to verify analyses drawn on static, crosslag, and dynamic correlations. We argue that this extension to causal analysis contains serious flaws and may be inappropriate in model building. The analysis is based on three aspects of measurement: similarities between the ?deficiency score? method and pre/post measurements, shifts in reference points, and patterns by which variables may change.
AB  - It has recently been suggested that impact and self-impact correlations be extended to verify analyses drawn on static, crosslag, and dynamic correlations. We argue that this extension to causal analysis contains serious flaws and may be inappropriate in model building. The analysis is based on three aspects of measurement: similarities between the ?deficiency score? method and pre/post measurements, shifts in reference points, and patterns by which variables may change.
